{{notability|Organizations|date=April 2014}} {{infobox Organization |name = Executive MBA Council |image = |image_border = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = EMBA Council |motto = |formation = 1981 |extinction = |type = NGO |status = |purpose = [[educational accreditation]] |headquarters = |location = |region_served = |membership = |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = http://www.emba.org |remarks = }} The '''Executive [[MBA]] Council''' is an [[educational accreditation]] council formed in 1981 to accredit [[business school|schools of business]] offering EMBA degrees worldwide. The council was formed with the assistance of the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] (AACSB International).<ref>[http://www.emba.org/about_member_list.html EMBA Council Members]</ref>
The council's stated [[Mission statement|mission]] is to promote the advancement of executive MBA worldwide through its partnerships, conference, and research and outreach activities.<ref>[https://www.efmd.org/index.php/blog/view/219-executive-mba-council-reports-on-key-trends EFMD] EFMD Executive MBA Council Reports on Key Trends, Retrieved April 14, 2014</ref> The EMBA Council is governed by a Board of Trustees, which consists mainly of the Deans or Program Directors of its business school members and sets goals on council initiatives.<ref>[http://www.emba.org/about_whoweare_board.htm Executive Council Board of Trustees]</ref>
The council is headquartered in Beckman Hall, [[Orange, California|Orange]], [[California]], [[United States]].
As of May 2010, the Executive MBA Council has accredited 237 full business schools on six continents and 18 corporate members.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}
